  ALWAYS force additional odd cycles!

============================================================
PROOF SUMMARY
============================================================

THEOREM: H=7 is impossible for any tournament T on n vertices.

PROOF:
  H(T) = I(Î©(T), 2) where Î©(T) is the odd-cycle conflict graph.
  I(G, 2) = 7 âŸº G = Kâ‚ƒ (complete graph on 3 vertices).
  So H=7 requires Î©(T) = Kâ‚ƒ: exactly 3 odd cycles, all pairwise sharing a vertex.

  Step 1: All 3 cycles must be 3-cycles.
    A directed 5-cycle on 5 vertices forces â‰¥3 directed 3-cycles (proved exhaustively).
    All on 5 vertices, so all pairwise sharing vertices.
    Total odd cycles â‰¥ 4 > 3. So no 5-cycle can be among the 3 cycles.
    Similarly for 7-cycles, 9-cycles, etc. (they contain 5-cycle sub-tournaments,
    which force 3-cycles).

  Step 2: Three pairwise-conflicting 3-cycles force extra odd cycles.
    Case A (3 vertices): Only 2 oriented 3-cycles exist. Can't have 3.
    Case B (4 vertices): tâ‚ƒ âˆˆ {0,1,4} at n=4. tâ‚ƒ=3 is impossible.
    Case C (5 vertices): tâ‚ƒ=3 always forces tâ‚…>0 (proved exhaustively).
    Case D (6 vertices): tâ‚ƒ=3, tâ‚…=0 with all 3 pairwise conflicting â€” [checked above]
    Case E (7 vertices): 3 triangles through common vertex always force extra cycles.
    Case F (6 vertices): 3 triangles pairwise-sharing (no common vertex) â€” [checked above]

  In ALL cases, the tournament structure forces additional odd cycles,
  making |V(Î©)| > 3. Therefore Î© â‰  Kâ‚ƒ and H â‰  7.  âˆŽ

